data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has these Thread.Abort patterns:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` |
| **ThreadAbortException catch** | `catch` block with rollback | `OperationCanceledException` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Preventing rethrow | Remove — check `IsCancellationRequested` instead |
| **Thread.Abort()** | `Stop()` method | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| **Blocking call interruption** | `GetNextItem()` may block | Token-aware waiting |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — migrated from ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — just let the loop condition exit naturally
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop in time — log a warning.
            // There is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort in .NET 8.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key Changes to `GetNextItem`

If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a queue), it **must** accept the token or cancellation will stall:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks forever, only Thread.Abort could break it
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks indefinitely
}

// AFTER — wakes up when cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If it uses `Thread.Sleep`, replace with:
```csharp
// BEFORE
Thread.Sleep(1000);

// AFTER — wakes immediately on cancellation
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(1000);
```

## Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Not passing token to blocking calls** | `CancellationToken` is cooperative — if `GetNextItem()` never checks it, `Stop()` hangs forever. This is the #1 migration failure. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to avoid swallowing unrelated cancellations. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers/callbacks. Always implement `IDisposable`. |
| **Expecting cancellation to be instant** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside long `ProcessItem` work. |
| **Lost cleanup logic** | Your `ThreadAbortException` catch did `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` — this is preserved in the `OperationCanceledException` catch. Don't delete it by accident. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort` had meaning** | It let the loop continue after abort. In the new model, `IsCancellationRequested` stays true permanently. If you need per-item cancellation (abort one item, continue the next), use a **linked CancellationTokenSource per item**. |

## If You Need Per-Item Abort (ResetAbort equivalent)

```csharp
while (!parentToken.IsCancellationRequested)
{
    using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(parentToken);
    try
    {
        var item = GetNextItem(parentToken);
        ProcessItem(item, itemCts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!parentToken.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // Only this item was cancelled — continue to next
        RollbackCurrentTransaction();
    }
}
```

The fundamental shift: **Thread.Abort was preemptive** (runtime injects an exception anywhere). **CancellationToken is cooperative** (your code must check it). Every blocking call in the chain needs the token passed through.
